SIMPLE: flux
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flux
<hw>Flux</hw> <pr>(fl⟦ucr⟧ks)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>fluxus</ets>, fr. <ets>fluere</ets>, <ets>fluxum</ets>, to flow:
cf.F. <ets>flux</ets>. See <er>Fluent</er>, and cf. 1st & 2d
<er>Floss</er>, <er>Flush</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 6.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of flowing; a continuous moving on or passing by, as of a
flowing stream; constant succession; change.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> By the perpetual <qex>flux</qex> of the liquids, a great part of
them is thrown out of the body.</q> <rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Her image has escaped the <qex>flux</qex> of things,⟦br⟧
And that same infant beauty that she wore⟦br⟧
Is fixed upon her now forevermore.</q> <rj><qau>Trench.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> Languages, like our bodies, are in a continual
<qex>flux</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Felton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The setting in of the tide toward the shore, -- the
ebb being called the <ant>reflux</ant>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The state of being liquid through heat;
fusion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Chem. & Metal.)</fld> <def>Any substance or mixture
used to promote the fusion of metals or minerals, as alkalies, borax,
lime, fluorite.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <stype>White flux</stype> is the residuum of the
combustion of a mixture of equal parts of niter and tartar. It consists
chiefly of the carbonate of potassium, and is white. -- <stype>Black
flux</stype> is the ressiduum of the combustion of one part of niter and
two of tartar, and consists essentially of a mixture of potassium
carbonate and charcoal.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A fluid discharge
from the bowels or other part; especially, an excessive and morbid
discharge; <as>as, the bloody <ex>flux</ex> or dysentery</as>. See
<er>Bloody flux</er>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The matter thus
discharged.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>The quantity of a fluid that
crosses a unit area of a given surface in a unit of time.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flux</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Flux
<hw>Flux</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>fluxus</ets>, p. p. of
<ets>fluere</ets>. See <er>Flux</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>Flowing;
unstable; inconstant; variable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>flux</qex> nature of all things here.</q>
<rj><qau>Barrow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flux</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Flux
<hw>Flux</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Fluxed</conjf> <pr>(fl⟦ucr⟧kst)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Fluxing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To affect, or bring
to a certain state, by flux.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He might fashionably and genteelly . . . have been dueled or⟦br⟧
<qex>fluxed</qex> into another world.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cause to become fluid; to fuse.</def>
<rj><au>Kirwan.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>To cause a discharge from; to
purge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fluxation</ent>⟦br⟧
